City of Brooklyn Park (Jeff Holstein, Gary Brown, Cindy Sherman)
This letter outlines the assumptions Westwood Professional Services proposes to
employ in conducting the AUAR traffic study for the proposed Gateway development
in the southwest quadrant of TH 169 and TH 610 in Brooklyn Park. The following
discussion covers assumptions made in four categories: study area, site development,
growth in background traffic volumes and roadway upgrades.
The Study Area figure in the appendix shows the roadways and intersections to be
analyzed in the study. These include:
Avenue from CSAH 202 (Zachary Lane) in Maple Grove to CSAH 103
(West Broadway Avenue) in Brooklyn Park, including the intersections at
Revere Lane, Jefferson Highway and TH 169; and
Also included will be the proposed full movement interchange at 101
TH 169, along with the proposed site access road intersections, one onto 93
As shown on the attached site plan, the proposed Gateway development consists of
1,337,000 sq. ft. of office space, 37,000 sq. ft. of restaurant and general retail, a 200-
room hotel and 510 condominium/townhouse units. The proposed plan includes
development on approximately 32 acres land currently owned by MnDOT that may
be made available after completion of the TH 610/TH 169 interchange
Based on these proposed land uses and sizes, the development is anticipated to
generate approximately three to four times more traffic than the forecast by SRF
Consulting Group in their City of Brooklyn Park Traffic Forecast Model, as
documented in SRF’s October 15, 2007 letter to the City of Brooklyn Park.
Preliminary trip generation estimates for the proposed development are attached.
Full build-out of the site is anticipated by the year 2019. Analysis will be performed
for existing volume conditions and for two development scenarios: 2020, one year
after full build-out, and the future design year of 2030.
An interim/Phase 1 development scenario will also be considered. At this time,
construction amounting to around 50% of the eventual total is anticipated to be
complete by 2013. This will be considered as “Phase 1” of the development. 2014
will accordingly be included as the Phase 1 design year.
Traffic volume assumptions for 2020 and 2030 are based on “Scenario B” from the
Brooklyn Park Traffic Forecast Model prepared by SRF for the City’s recent
Comprehensive Plan Update. Scenario B was chosen based on the City’s direction
and because it represents their current “Best Guess” estimate for development in
Brooklyn Park in the upcoming decades. Scenario B reflects a 70% higher number of
jobs in Brooklyn Park than the “Scenario A” alternative assumed by the Metropolitan
Council, and a 55% lower number of jobs than Scenario C, the Target North Campus
Since the model prepared by SRF was for Brooklyn Park only, it did not detail ADT
forecasts for the Maple Grove roads that are within the study area. Therefore, it is
assumed that growth in the portion of the study area within the City of Maple Grove
will be at a rate similar to that of Brooklyn Park as forecasted in the SRF memo.
The procedure used to develop future traffic volume forecasts will be similar to the
process used in a study for a similar development in the area (Astra Village) as
suggested by Jeff Holstein at the City of Brooklyn Park:
Use the 2020 and 2030 ADT forecasts from the SRF memo Scenario "B"
Determine the expected land use and traffic generation for the proposed
development site as assumed in the SRF model,
Determine the expected directional orientation of the modeled site land use
and assign expected generation to the adjacent roadway system based on this,
Subtract the expected site traffic from model land use scenario from each
respective 2020 and 2030 forecast (from step "a") to get 2020 and 2030
Use the proportion between the background forecasts to existing ADT to
adjust any AM or PM peak hour counts at key intersections to 2020 or 2030
AM or PM background forecasts, and
Add site-generated trips to step "e" to get appropriate 2020 or 2030 AM or
To help gauge the anticipated impact and assist scoping, three figures included in the
appendix show preliminary ADT volumes for existing conditions and for the 2020
and 2030 development cases. On the 2020 and 2030 figures, volumes are provided
for three scenarios: (1) the projected background ADT for that year, (2) the Brooklyn
Park Scenario B total ADT forecast for that year, and (3) the total ADT forecast with
the proposed Gateway development in place.
The preliminary trip generation estimates for the site are also included. Pass-By and
Shared trips were estimated using data from ITE’s Trip Generation Handbook, 2nd
Edition, to the extent possible, and making consistent, conservative assumptions
thereafter. Based on the primarily office-oriented nature of the site, study of the AM
and PM peak hours is proposed.
Also included in the appendix are the trip distribution assumptions used to generate
these preliminary ADT forecasts. Two distribution assumptions were used; a “Pre-
610” and a “Post-610,” corresponding to conditions before and after completion of
TH 610 from TH 169 to I-94. The distribution assumptions are based on
Metropolitan Council’s 2020 and 2030 forecasts for TAZ 754.
Several roadways in the area are planned to be upgraded between now and the

TH 610 from TH 169 in Brooklyn Park to I-94 in Maple Grove, between 2020

Highway, with no access to Jefferson Highway, as planned. The nearest
access to TH 610 to the west at that time will be to the west of the site at
CSAH 202 (Zachary Lane), or alternatively via CSAH 81.

Regarding roadway assumptions, I believe we are planning on reconstructing CSAH-103 as a 4-
The assumptions for reconstruction of 93rd Avenue (CSAH-30) are probably OK - the segment
west of TH-169 is currently designated as a provisional project (i.e. no funds) in our 2008-

Thanks you for sending me the Gateway TIS Assumptions. Our comments are as follows:
1) Please analyze the TH 610/TH 169 intechange and the TH 169/101st St. intersection.
2) The development scenarios refer to developing on 32 acres of Mn/DOT land at the TH 610/TH
169 interchange. This assumption probably shouldn't be made.
3) Include both am and pm peak hour volumes and LOS's.
4) Model both pre and post mitigation.
5) Please involve us during key points in the study - e.g. when mitigation measures are
identified, when preliminary results are in, etc.
Please let me know if you have any questions.

increased traffic would outweigh decreased access. Furthermore, in order to really make an educated guess of what type
of roadway is preferred, we would want to see the following data at some point:
---Post-development corridor traffic counts on Central Ave. (based on current counts) for each alternative
---Post-development intersection traffic counts on Central Ave. (based on current counts) for each alternative
---Data showing traffic changes in the Northeast section of Osseo for each alternative
3. The main access on County Rd. 30 should be a three-way access. Because we are concerned about increased
north/south traffic on our residential streets from County Rd. 30 to CSAH 81, the main access should not be connected
with, for example, 4th or 5th Ave. NE. Because a three-way access is preferred, we would assume that a round-a- bout
4. While we do not want a street connection with the main access, trail/pedestrian access from Osseo into the

5. Regarding stormwater, Osseo does not want any increased pressure on the stormwater ditch that flows through St.

Please let me know if you have any questions. Thanks.

It will be interesting to see if Mn/DOT agrees with the idea of a temporary TH-610 connection

In my October 1, 2008 letter, I made reference to the System Optimization Study "SOS."
Please note that this is the incorrect name for this study. The actual name has yet to be
determined. Further, although we anticipate doing some type of system study with the
Metropolitan Council, it will not evaluate individual corridor segments as stated in the
letter. Please disregard the "System Optimization Study" portion of my letter. I regret any
confusion this may have caused you or others. Please let me know if you have any questions.

page.text: The recent passage by Congress of the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act,
a.k.a. the “Stimulus” bill, is likely to affect several of the assumptions made regarding
timing of roadway infrastructure improvements within the Gateway AUAR traffic
study area. Specifically, it now appears likely that construction of TH 610 from TH
169 to CSAH 81 will begin this summer.
This letter outlines the changes to assumptions that we propose to make as part of the
traffic impact study for the Gateway AUAR.
As part of the TH 610 project, the systems interchange of TH 169 and TH 610 will be
converted to a full cloverleaf, eliminating the at-grade south ramp intersection. The
proposed study area eliminates this intersection, leaving the following intersections:
TH 610 signalized south ramp intersection (folded diamond)
Two design years/development scenarios will be studied as part of this AUAR traffic
impact study. The 2020 design year will not be included with this study, following
the City of Brooklyn Park’s suggestion, in order to provide focus on the critical near-
term and long-term horizons and to avoid making premature forecasts involving the
development on the Gateway site is to occur after the initial build phase, study of an
interim design year will occur. As this study will take place after completion of the
TH 610 project and after Phase 1 of the Gateway project, it will have a much more
accurate picture of traffic patterns at the time, yielding more a more useful and
targeted Mitigation plan for the infrastructure needs of Phase 2 of the Gateway
The first design year/Phase 1 of the proposed development will be assumed to include
225,000 s.f. of office, with completion by 2014. The year after build-out, 2015 is
assumed as the initial design year. The final build phase (design year 2030) will be
assumed to consist of 1,200,000 sq. ft. of office space, 37,000 sq. ft. of restaurant and
general retail, a 200-room hotel, 310 condominium/townhouse units and 200 units of
In contrast to the original set of assumptions, the AUAR will NOT include
development on the approximately 32 acres of land currently owned by MnDOT
immediately adjacent to the TH 169/TH 610 interchange. This change was made
after comments received from MnDOT that suggested that new stormwater
regulations would preclude development on this land.
Data from the Metropolitan Council regional model will be used in forecasting No-
Build traffic volumes and distribution patterns for 2015. The model will be updated
to include completion of TH 610 to CSAH 81. Existing turning movement volumes
will be factored up/down in proportion to the ADT changes on the two associated
roadways for each movement throughout the network.
Based on the information received from Met Council, the following annual growth
rate percentages will be applied to derive 2015 volumes:
West of TH 169: -2% (reduction due to shift to TH 610)
West Broadway Avenue: 3% (higher growth due to added capacity)
No-Build scenario traffic volume assumptions for 2030 will remain unchanged from
the earlier analysis. These were based on “Scenario B” from the Brooklyn Park
Traffic Forecast Model prepared by SRF for the City’s recent Comprehensive Plan
Update. Scenario B represents the City of Brooklyn Park’s current “Best Guess”
estimate for development in the upcoming decades. It reflects a 70% higher number

The preliminary trip generation estimates for the site are attached. Pass-By and
Shared trips (for the 2030 design year only) were estimated using data from ITE’s

Your roadway network assumptions are OK with me - the major roadway additions agree with the
network we used in our 2030 HC-TSP model. The TH-169 / 93rd Avenue interchange and 93rd
Avenue west of TH-169 are currently shown as "provisional" projects in our CIP - i.e. we do
not have any programmed funding for these projects. These projects are being considered as
candidates for the next federal solicitation this spring.
Our 2030 HC-TSP is based on a land use approach for trip estimation. The future land uses
come from the individual city comprehensive plans plus clarification discussions with city
staff. Our forecasts include the proposed full buildout of the Gateway development and the
Target Campus (plus other development on the south side of TH-610). Our model also
incorporates the Met Council mode split assumptions.
